@Chook Python `for` loops work nothing like in C, but that often makes them easier to understand, as you can't do weird things that easily.
`for t in text:` would first get an iterator for the (iterable) value of `text`, an object that will walk the string. Then, the loop will request items from the iterator (in this case single characters), and assign them to `t`, until the iterator is exhausted (at the string's end).
Same with `for i in range(len(text)):`, `range` returns an iterator (and an iterator, asked for an iterator, will return itself). So if you changed `i` in the loop, it would not have any effect on the following iterations, as the state is kept in the iterator.

